                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>         In giving a structure via tables like this, there's no need to separately specify the set of values, since you can read those off the edges of the tables.
        By packaging everything up into a structure in this way, we make it easy to change from one structure to another, to think about different kinds of valuations we might want to draw on, beyond just Boolean ones.
        In a moment, we'll look at a few other example structures, besides this Boolean one.
        But first, I want to look a bit at some uses of Boolean valuations.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" hidden-when-empty="true">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:authors />
        <fr:title text="Backlinks">Backlinks</fr:title>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
              <fr:month>3</fr:month>
              <fr:day>18</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/004O/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>004O</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/lectures/004O/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="A first example">A first example</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>            As a warmup, say that a Boolean valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> is a <html:strong>counterexample</html:strong> to an argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \;/\; A]]></fr:tex> when every premise in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> gets the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> on valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> and the conclusion <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> gets value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>.
            If an argument has any counterexamples, then we can see that the truth of its premises does <html:em>not</html:em> guarantee the truth of its conclusion---the counterexample shows a way to distribute truth values among the atomic formulas that makes the premises all true without making the conclusion true.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            So we can get a logic from our Boolean valuations like this: if any Boolean valuation is a counterexample to an argument, this logic counts the argument as invalid.
            On the other hand, if no Boolean valuation is a counterexample to the argument, then this logic counts the argument as valid.
            This is a very widely used logic, called <html:strong>classical logic</html:strong>.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>18</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/004P/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>004P</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/004P/</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Side note</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Recall the history here, though: this only goes back to the 19th century.
            So the "classical" here is more like the "classical" in "classical music" than it is like the "classical" in "classical architecture".</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>            Let's return to some earlier example arguments, to see how they fare in classical logic.
            First, think about <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  q \;/\; p]]></fr:tex>.
            To see whether this argument is classically valid or not, we should ask: is any Boolean valuation a counterexample to this argument?
            Remember, a counterexample to this argument is a valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p \land  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
            By looking at <fr:link href="/lectures/003N/" title="The Boolean structure" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/003N/" display-uri="003N" type="local">the Boolean structure</fr:link>, though, you can see that this is impossible: if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, then no matter what <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(q)]]></fr:tex> is we also have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p \land  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
            So no Boolean valuation is a counterexample to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  q \;/\; p]]></fr:tex>.
            As a result, this argument is classically valid.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            For a contrasting example, think about <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \lor  q \;/\; p]]></fr:tex>.
            Is any Boolean valuation a counterexample to this argument?
            A counterexample to this argument would be a valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p \lor  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
            Is there any such <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w]]></fr:tex>?
            Yes, there is.
            Since there is always a valuation for any combination of values for our atomic sentences, consider any valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>.
            In any such valuation, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p \lor  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, so any such valuation is a counterexample to this argument.
            As a result, this argument is not classically valid.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            Just like the Boolean structure, classical logic doesn't have to be interpreted as about truth.
            Recall that if we're thinking about electrical circuits, each sentence represents a component of the circuit that can be on or off.
            In this case, when an argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \;/\; A]]></fr:tex> is classically valid, it means that whenever all the components represented by sentences in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> are on, then the component represented by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> must also be on.
            A counterexample to the argument would be some way of setting things up so that all the premise components are on and the conclusion component is off.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            What about arguments <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \;/\; A]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> is the <html:em>empty</html:em> set of premises?
            Remember, we can have arguments with no premises.
            What does it take for a valuation to be a counterexample to one of these?
            The same thing it takes to be a counterexample to any argument: it has to make all the premises take the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and the conclusion take value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
            To interpret this, we need to remember <fr:link href="/lectures/000F/" title="Logicians' Weird Habit 2" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/000F/" display-uri="000F" type="local">logicians' weird habit 2</fr:link>: if there are no Xs, then "all Xs are Ys" automatically counts as true.
            So when there are no premises, "all the premises take value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> on this valuation" is always true, no matter what valuation we're looking at.
            That means that, for a valuation to be a counterexample to an argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\;/\; A]]></fr:tex> with no premises, all it needs to do is take the sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
            The none premises are automatic.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            That means that an argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\;/\; A]]></fr:tex> is classically valid whenever the sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> takes the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> on <html:em>every</html:em> Boolean valuation.
            Such sentences are called <html:em>theorems</html:em>.
            Just like "valid" or "invalid", "theorem" is always relative to a logic.
            A sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> might be a theorem in one logic but not another, because the argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\;/\; A]]></fr:tex> is valid in the first logic but not the other.
            Indeed, we'll see examples like that soon.
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>18</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/004Q/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>004Q</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/004Q/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Theorem">Theorem</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>A <html:strong>theorem</html:strong> of a logic is a sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> such that the argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\;/\; A]]></fr:tex> is valid in the logic.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>            One notable theorem of classical logic is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \lor  \neg  p]]></fr:tex>.
            In setting up our Boolean valuations, we forced every sentence to be true or false on each valuation.
            Since negation takes falsity to truth, on every valuation one or the other of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  p]]></fr:tex> is true.
            And a disjunction is true when at least one of the disjuncts is true.
            So <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \lor  \neg  p]]></fr:tex> comes out true no matter what value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> has.
            This appears in the resulting logic: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\;/\; p \lor  \neg  p]]></fr:tex> is a valid argument.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            In fact, we can go farther.
            For <html:em>any sentence</html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, the sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \lor  \neg  A]]></fr:tex> is a classical theorem.
            Make sure you see how to interpret this.
            There's no particular sentence "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \lor  \neg  A]]></fr:tex>" in our language; <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> isn't part of the language at all.
            Rather, what I'm saying is that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \lor  \neg  p]]></fr:tex> is a classical theorem, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \lor  \neg  q]]></fr:tex> is a classical theorem, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \land  q) \lor  \neg  (p \land  q)]]></fr:tex> is a classical theorem, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg \neg (p \lor  \neg  r) \lor  \neg \neg \neg  (p \lor  \neg  r)]]></fr:tex> is a classical theorem, and so on.
            I'm using <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> as a variable, to make a claim about lots of different sentences all at once.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            Before we move on, let's look at one more example.
            Think about the argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p, \neg  p \;/\; q]]></fr:tex>.
            Is this classically valid?
            To find out, we need to think whether it has any classical counterexamples.
            A classical counterexample would be a Boolean valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p) = v(\neg  p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, since it would need to make both premises true and the conclusion not true.
            But this can't happen; if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  p)]]></fr:tex> can't also be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, because of how negation is handled in Boolean valuations.
            So there are no classical counterexamples to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p, \neg  p \;/\; q]]></fr:tex>.
            This argument is classically valid.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            That sometimes can throw people for a loop; it seems like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  p]]></fr:tex> have nothing to do with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>!
            So how can the argument be valid?
            This is where it's important to remember how logic works: we lay out precise and clear definitions, and we see where they follow.
            The way we've set up classical logic, it just falls out that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p, \neg  p \;/\; q]]></fr:tex> is valid.
            If it seems to you like arguments like this shouldn't be valid, that might give you a reason to explore logics other than classical logic.
            This is one of the ways different logics will differ from each other.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
